<scenario>
The agent A provided the following violation scenario:
The call to _MHD_POISON_MEMORY(pool->memory, pool->size) is a no-op when the poisoning macro is defined to (void)0 (i.e. poisoning/sanitizer support is disabled). In that configuration the statement executes but has no effect and could be removed without changing program behaviour, so it constitutes dead code (Rule 2.2). If, instead, _MHD_POISON_MEMORY expands to a real instrumentation function, then it is not dead — the violation only occurs when the macro is defined as a no-op.
</scenario>
